{"summary": "The available evidence from action documents provides limited direct comparison between connecting existing semi-natural habitats versus replanting native forest for boosting bee populations. Action 10 ("Connect areas of natural or semi-natural habitat for bees") found no evidence of the effects on wild bee communities of connecting patches of natural or semi-natural habitat. Similarly, action 6 ("Increase the proportion of natural or semi-natural habitat in the farmed landscape") found no evidence demonstrating the effects of restoring natural or semi-natural habitat on bee diversity or abundance in neighbouring farms. Action 5 ("Protect existing natural or semi-natural habitat to prevent conversion to agriculture") also captured no evidence for the effects of protecting areas of natural or semi-natural habitat on bee populations or communities.

However, there is substantial evidence for the effectiveness of creating new flowering habitat. Action 19 ("Sow uncropped arable field margins with a native wild flower seed mix") found that five replicated trials in the UK showed that uncropped field margins sown with wild flowers support a higher abundance and species richness of foraging bumblebees than cropped field edges, grassy margins or naturally regenerated uncropped margins. Action 442 ("Plant nectar flower mixture/wildflower strips") found that 80 individual studies investigated the effects of flowering strips on biodiversity, with 64 studies showing some benefits to one or more wildlife groups. Specifically, 65 studies reported effects on invertebrates, with 50 reporting positive effects and 41 studies finding evidence that flower strips had a positive influence on invertebrate numbers with increased abundance, species richness/diversity, or both.

Action 3932 ("Plant nectar flower mixture/wildflower strips") found that 23 studies evaluated the effects of planting nectar flower mixtures on butterflies and moths, with multiple studies finding that sown wildflower strips had higher species richness and diversity of butterflies and moths than conventional field margins, unsown margins, cropped fields or conventional grassland.", "action_ids": ["10","6","5","19","442","3932"], "query": "Is it more effective to connect existing semi-natural habitats or to re-plant native forest to boost bee populations?"}

